    <section id="id1166281445413">
      <title>Finished Drawings</title>
      <para id="id1166279190972">Finished drawings survive for eight of the ten pictorial designs that were included within the 1894 edition. Because they were eventually printed by photomechanical means, these original drawings “have an even greater nervous quality of line” than the printed illustrations, writes Stephen Calloway (<emphasis effect="italics">Charles Ricketts: Subtle and Fantastic Decorator</emphasis> [Thames and Hudson, 1977], p. 16). No finished drawings are known to exist for the illustrations printed facing Wilde’s lines “Get hence, you loathsome mystery ! Hideous animal, get hence !” and “Foul snake and speckled adder with their young ones crawl from stone to stone/ For ruined is the house and prone the great rose-marble monolith !”</para>
